193: ## Why This App Exists (The Fragmentation Problem)
194: 
195: **The problem:** Developers spin up their own ERC-20 testnet tokens and ERC-7984 wrappers instead of using the ones that already exist in the official Zama Wrappers Registry. That fragments the ecosystem: every team ships against a slightly different set of tokens, integrations don't compose, and users end up with a wallet full of look-alike confidential assets that don't actually interoperate.
196: 
197: **Concrete example of fragmentation:** Team A deploys "USDC" at 0xABC... and their wrapper at 0x123.... Team B deploys "USDC" at 0xDEF... and their wrapper at 0x456.... Now a user has two "confidential USDC" tokens in their wallet — neither works with the other team's dApp. A developer building a new DeFi protocol has to choose which set to support, or support both. The ecosystem fragments.
198: 
199: **The solution:** Turn the official registry into a usable product — an app that every developer and user can point to, where the canonical ERC-20 to ERC-7984 pairs are easy to find, easy to wrap/unwrap, easy to decrypt, and easy to extend with new pairs through a documented process.
200: 
201: **Our north star:** Make using existing wrappers the path of least resistance and reduce fragmentation across the ecosystem.
202: 
203: **How we prove this works:** The app must be so good that a developer who was about to deploy their own test token instead thinks: "Why bother? The official registry already has USDC, USDT, WETH, BRON, ZAMA, tGBP, and XAUt. I'll just use those." If we achieve that, we've solved the fragmentation problem.
