742: ## Why Canonical Pairs Matter (The Fragmentation Problem)
743: 
744: This is the CORE of the bounty. The app exists because of this problem. Every design decision should reinforce: "use the official registry, not your own tokens."
745: 
746: ### The Problem (Detailed)
747: 
748: - Developers spin up their own ERC-20 testnet tokens and ERC-7984 wrappers
749: - Every team ships against a slightly different set of tokens
750: - Integrations don't compose — same "USDC" token in one app is a different contract in another
751: - Users end up with a wallet full of look-alike confidential assets that don't interop
752: - New developers waste time deploying wrappers that already exist
753: - The Zama ecosystem fragments into incompatible silos
754: 
755: ### The Solution
756: 
757: One app. One registry. All canonical pairs. Zero fragmentation.
758: 
759: The app makes the official registry so easy to use that there's no reason to deploy your own tokens. The canonical pairs are: discoverable (one registry read), accessible (faucet gives you test tokens immediately), usable (wrap/unwrap/decrypt works), and extensible (add new pairs through documented process).
760: 
761: ### Comparison Table (for README and in-app)
762: 
763: | Fragmentation (bad) | Canonical (good) |
764: |---------------------|-------------------|
765: | Each team deploys own test tokens | Official cTokenMocks on Sepolia |
766: | Wallet full of non-interoperable assets | All wrappers registered in one registry |
767: | Integrations don't compose | Same token pairs across all dApps |
768: | Hard to find which tokens are "real" | One registry, one source of truth |
769: | New teams waste time deploying wrappers | Just use the existing ones |
770: | No standard addresses | Registered pairs have canonical addresses |
771: 
