781: ## Extensibility: Two Paths to Add a New Pair
782: 
783: The bounty requires a "documented process for adding new ERC-20 to ERC-7984 pairs." We provide TWO paths, because different developers have different needs. Both are documented in the README with step-by-step instructions.
784: 
785: ### Path A: Local Config (for development/testing)
786: 
787: **When to use:** You're developing a new wrapper contract and want to test it in the app before registering on-chain.
788: 
789: **Steps:**
790: 1. Open `lib/tokens.ts`
791: 2. Add a new entry to the `TOKEN_PAIRS` array:
792:    - `erc20`: your token's symbol, address, decimals, name
793:    - `erc7984`: your wrapper's symbol, address, decimals, name
794: 3. Save the file — the app hot-reloads
795: 4. Your new pair appears in the registry browser
796: 
797: **Pros:** Instant, no gas, no on-chain interaction
798: **Cons:** Only visible in your local deployment, not in the canonical registry
799: 
800: ### Path B: On-Chain Registration (for production)
801: 
802: **When to use:** Your wrapper is production-ready and you want it in the official registry that all apps read from.
803: 
804: **Steps:**
805: 1. Deploy your ERC-20 token contract on Sepolia
806: 2. Deploy your ERC-7984 wrapper contract on Sepolia
807: 3. Verify your wrapper implements IERC7984 (interface ID `0x4958f2a4`)
808: 4. Call `registerConfidentialToken(erc20Address, wrapperAddress)` on the registry contract (`0x2f0750Bbb0A246059d80e94c454586a7F27a128e`)
809: 5. The registry validates: ERC-165 support, no duplicates, neither address is zero
810: 6. Your pair now appears in EVERY app that reads the on-chain registry
811: 
812: **Pros:** Canonical, visible everywhere, official
813: **Cons:** Requires gas, requires registry owner to call (or governance)
814: 
815: ### How the App Handles Both
816: 
817: The app merges on-chain pairs (from `getTokenConfidentialTokenPairs()`) with local config pairs (from `lib/tokens.ts`). Local pairs override on-chain pairs by ERC-20 address. This means:
818: - Official pairs always appear (from on-chain)
819: - Developers can test custom pairs locally (from config)
820: - The merge is transparent — the UI shows which source each pair came from
